{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8e81e493-6fa7-41bb-9d0b-a60f10c7f63f","content":"The standard approach is to **introduce a file system abstraction** — an interface you can mock in tests:\n\n```csharp\npublic interface IFileSystem\n{\n    string ReadAllText(string path);\n    void WriteAllText(string path, string contents);\n    bool DirectoryExists(string path);\n}\n```\n\nThen create a real implementation that wraps `System.IO`:\n\n```csharp\npublic class FileSystem : IFileSystem\n{\n    public string ReadAllText(string path) => File.ReadAllText(path);\n    public void WriteAllText(string path, string contents) => File.WriteAllText(path, contents);\n    public bool DirectoryExists(string path) => Directory.Exists(path);\n}\n```\n\n**Inject `IFileSystem`** via constructor into any class that needs file access. In tests, pass a mock/fake instead.\n\nAlternatively, the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package provides a ready-made `IFileSystem` with a `MockFileSystem` for testing — saves you from maintaining your own abstraction.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1dbb0694-b950-46dd-bbcd-3060cf811179","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making file system operations testable in a .NET/C# project. They have `File.WriteAllText`, `File.ReadAllText`, and `Directory.Exists` calls scattered across their project and want to know how to make them testable.\n\nThis is a general software engineering question, not a task requiring code changes. I should give a concise answer about the standard approach: introducing a file system abstraction (interface) that can be mocked in tests.\n\nLet me give a concise, practical answer.","outputTokens":383,"requestId":"3400:1F19B7:C3256F:E50531:69F40906"},"id":"a47d293c-b011-4c50-8c2d-02dcf31000c1","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:59:47.669Z","parentId":"505ae6c0-9d6a-4a95-b96d-0388dc29ddd2"}
